# Macro Academy Article Template

You are writing for **Physiq Macro Academy** (Next.js app). Every article MUST follow this template.

**Registry field names:** In `lib/academy/articles.ts`, the Markdown field is **`body`** (string). When drafting, you may call the full Markdown `bodyMarkdown` for clarity, but the shipped object must use **`body`**.

---

## 1) Purpose & audience

- One primary reader intent (e.g. “set macros for fat loss as a woman who lifts”).
- Secondary intents become **links** to other guides, not new H2 sections that repeat the same thesis.
- Tone: clear, non-clinical, **general fitness education**; flag medical conditions; no diagnosis or treatment claims.

---

## 2) URL & slug

- **Slug:** lowercase, hyphenated, descriptive, stable (`best-macros-for-women`). No dates, no marketing fluff.
- Match slug to **title promise**; avoid clickbait that the body does not deliver.

---

## 3) Title (viral + honest)

- Pattern: **[Specific outcome or tension] + [Qualifier] + [Optional twist in parenthesis]**.
- Must be true after reading the article; avoid “secret,” “doctors hate,” absolute cures.
- Length: ~50–70 characters ideal for SERP; keep under ~65 where possible.

---

## 4) SEO metadata (fill every field)

- **metaTitle:** Unique; includes primary keyword once; brand suffix if required (`| Physiq`).
- **metaDescription:** 150–160 characters; **benefit + who it’s for + soft CTA** (calculator/guide); no duplicate of title.
- **excerpt:** 1–2 sentences for cards/previews; distinct from metaDescription.

---

## 5) Taxonomy

- **categoryId:** One academy category (e.g. `women`, `fat-loss`) — aligns with site IA (see `lib/academy/categories.ts`).
- **tags:** 3–6 relevant tags; consistent naming with existing articles.

---

## 6) Article body structure (Markdown)

- Article length **1400–2000 words**.

**Order (do not shuffle without reason):**

1. **Hero intro (1 short paragraph)** — promise + constraint (what this is / isn’t). Often maps to **`heroIntro`** in the registry (falls back to excerpt if omitted).
2. **Problem framing** — 1–2 short paragraphs OR **one** tight “Key links” box (max 3–5 bullets), not a wall of bold one-liners.
3. **Core teaching** — tables/steps only where they improve scannability (Myth vs Reality, numbered steps).
4. **Implementation** — calculator usage, ranges, **when to adjust** (trends, not single days).
   - **`## How to use the Macro Calculator` (and close variants):** Must mirror the real **`<form>`** in `components/MacroCalculator.tsx`. **First subsection = UI steps only** (`### In the calculator (follow the form)`): body stats (weight, height, age; optional body fat % with the form’s accuracy line if useful), **Sex** (Male / Female), **Goal** (Cut Fat, Build Muscle, Maintain, Body Recomposition), **Activity level** (honest average week), **Eating style** (note keto / carnivore / PSMF carb–fat logic), **Dietary restrictions & preferences** (toggles + optional other notes), then **Calculate Macros** → calorie + macro gram outputs. **Do not** present manual “set protein, then fat %, then carbs” as numbered *calculator* steps—that is interpretation, not the form. Put interpretation under separate headings (e.g. `### After you calculate`, `### Understanding your numbers`).
5. **FAQ** — **one** consolidated FAQ section (group by theme); no “FAQ part 2/3/4” unless truly distinct audiences.
6. **Closing** — one paragraph + **one** primary CTA (e.g. Macro Calculator).
7. **Related** — handled by `relatedGuideSlugs` / `relatedMacroSlugs` + short “Next reads” list in body; **avoid** duplicating the same idea in 10+ `## Appendix:` blocks.

**Forbidden patterns:**

- Dozens of parallel `## Appendix:` sections that repeat the same thesis.
- Multiple fragmented FAQ blocks with overlapping questions.
- Long chains of “phrase—[link]” without prose context.

---

## 7) Cross-links & internal linking

- **relatedGuideSlugs:** 5–8 guides — **highest relevance** only (published slugs only).
- **relatedMacroSlugs:** 5–8 macro program pages/calculators — match user phase (slugs must exist under the project’s SEO macro pages).
- **In-body links:** 1–2 per major section max; prefer **contextual** sentences over link stacks.
- Every cross-link must answer: “Would the reader need this **now** or should it be sidebar only?”

---

## 8) Dates & authorship

- **publishedAt** / **updatedAt:** ISO dates (`YYYY-MM-DD`); **updatedAt** when meaningfully revised.
- **author:** Consistent house name unless byline is real.
- **status:** `"published"` | `"draft"`; **featured** optional for hub.

---

## 9) Quality gate (before ship)

- [ ] Title ↔ body promise aligned
- [ ] Meta unique vs other articles
- [ ] No duplicate FAQ answers
- [ ] Medical/high-risk topics disclaimed once, visibly
- [ ] Primary CTA clear
- [ ] Slug readable in isolation

---

## Output format when asked to “draft an article”

Provide YAML or a bullet list of all fields the app expects, then the full Markdown body.

**Include at minimum:**

`slug`, `title`, `metaTitle`, `metaDescription`, `excerpt`, `categoryId`, `tags`, `heroIntro`, `body` (or draft label `bodyMarkdown` — must become **`body`** in `articles.ts`), `relatedGuideSlugs`, `relatedMacroSlugs`, `publishedAt`, `updatedAt`, `author`, `status` (and `featured` if used).

Then output the full Markdown for **`body`**, following the section order and forbidden patterns above.
